# FB Activity Log Extension — Automation Flow

The extension at `tools/fb_activity_log_extension/` is driven by the
**Chrome DevTools Protocol** from `automation/drive_via_cdp.py`. This is
the **default flow** — do not ask the user to click through the wizard
side panel by hand unless the automation is genuinely broken and a fix
would take longer than the manual run.

## End-to-end commands

```bash
# 1) Bring Chrome up with the debug port (idempotent — safe to run before every iteration).
#    First run rebuilds a slim profile copy under
#    ~/Library/Application Support/Google/Chrome-debug-9222 (~800MB);
#    later runs are no-ops if the port is already serving.
bash tools/fb_activity_log_extension/automation/start_chrome.sh

# 2) Fast feedback iteration (default mode). Single year (current year),
#    skip media, capped at 50 items. Target wall time: <5 min.
uv run --with websockets --no-project python3 \
  tools/fb_activity_log_extension/automation/drive_via_cdp.py

# 3) Variants for iteration
... drive_via_cdp.py --phase comments         # iterate on comments side
... drive_via_cdp.py --year 2019              # target a specific historical year
... drive_via_cdp.py --with-media             # opt media tab-enrichment back in
... drive_via_cdp.py --max-items 10           # tighter cap for faster smoke tests

# 4) FULL unbounded scrape — only when no known issues, no expected
#    iteration. Takes 30 min - several hours. Posts + comments are
#    separate invocations.
... drive_via_cdp.py --mode full --phase posts
... drive_via_cdp.py --mode full --phase comments
```

## Rule: Default iteration mode is ITER. Full runs only when nothing's expected to change.

While iterating on an issue or a novel behaviour, **always start with
`--mode iter`** (the default). A single year with `MAX_ITEMS=50` should
finish in <5 min and surface the bug-of-interest just as well as a
23-year run.

Reach for `--mode full` only when:
1. No code change is pending (the unbounded run is the final import,
   not a debugging step).
2. Iter mode has already confirmed the fix on the smallest scope.
3. You've explicitly told the user "this is going to take 30+ min".

A full run as the first attempt at a fix is wasted — you'll spend an
hour waiting for evidence that an iter run could have produced in three
minutes.

## Rule: Time every run. Don't accept >5 min iter without a reason.

The driver logs `elapsed=<seconds>` and emits a `WARNING` when an iter
run exceeds `ITER_TARGET_SECONDS` (currently 5 min). When that fires:

1. **Narrow the scope further** — drop to `--max-items 5`, or pick a
   year known to be sparse for the user (e.g. `--year 2014`).
2. **Profile the slow path** — look at the per-year `yearMs` numbers in
   the JSON output; one slow year usually means a per-post tab
   enrichment loop, not a 23-year iteration.
3. **Document the cost** — if a slow iter is unavoidable (e.g. the
   bug only manifests with media on), add a note in your PR / commit
   message rather than silently accepting drift.

The 5-min ceiling is a budget, not a hard limit. Adjust
`ITER_TARGET_SECONDS` in `drive_via_cdp.py` if a project change
genuinely raises the floor (and update this rule with the reason).

## Benchmark reference (2026-05-19, current-year posts harvest)

| Scope | Wall time | Stopped because | Why |
|---|---|---|---|
| `--mode iter` (cap=10, current default) | ~15–30s | `capPosts` | Cap-stop short-circuits |
| `--max-items 5` | 15.5s | `capPosts` | Single CDP round-trip enough |
| `--max-items 50` | 169.5s | `scrollStable` | Stable-loop dominates (25 rounds × ~6s) |
| `--mode full --phase posts` (23 years, with media) | ~58 min | per-year `scrollStable` | All 23 years + tab enrichment for media |

**Key insight:** the content script's scroll-stable detection waits 25
consecutive rounds (~150s) for new items before stopping. That's the
bulk of every harvest's wall time. A cap of 5–10 fires `capPosts` /
`capComments` first and skips the stable-wait entirely.

If iter regularly exceeds 30s on `cap=10`, something else is slow
(tab navigation timeout, FB throttling, media enrichment). Profile
the `yearMs` field in the JSON output before assuming it's just "the
harvest being slow".

## Architecture (so future-you doesn't relearn it)

- **Why we don't drive the side panel directly:** Playwright MCP launches
  its own Chromium with a separate profile — no extension, no FB
  session. The side panel is browser UI, not a navigable page, so we
  can't reach it through normal page-evaluation APIs.
- **What we drive instead:** the extension's MV3 **service worker**.
  Chrome exposes the SW as a CDP target. `Runtime.evaluate` against
  that target runs JS with full `chrome.*` access — same context the
  side panel UI uses to call `chrome.tabs.sendMessage(RUN_PHASE,…)`.
  The wizard's per-month/year iteration + merge logic lives in
  `build_driver_js()` as a port of `runMultiMonthSession`.
- **Why we kill the user's main Chrome:** Chrome 136+ blocks
  `--remote-debugging-port` on the default user-data-dir for security.
  We copy the user's `Default` profile to a separate dir (excluding
  ~1.4GB of caches → 800MB), then launch Chrome against that copy.
  The user's real Chrome session is preserved — relaunch normally
  ("Restore previous windows") to recover tabs.
- **Why we wake the service worker:** MV3 SWs sleep aggressively. The
  driver navigates the FB tab to an activity-log URL, which re-injects
  the content script, which sends an init message to the SW — waking
  it. The driver auto-detects a dormant SW and runs the wake step.

## Rule: Don't use `--mode full` for a whole archive — loop iter year-by-year

`--mode full --from-year 2018 --to-year 2026` (the full archive) tries to
run **one giant `media_zip` IPC call** across all years. Chrome MV3 caps
`chrome.tabs.sendMessage` async responses at ~5 minutes. A full-archive
`enrichMediaFromPermalinkFetches` runs ~30 minutes (we observed 686
reshare candidates × ~700 ms Googlebot fetch each). The IPC channel
dies long before the work finishes; the driver gets:

  `"A listener indicated an asynchronous response by returning true,
   but the message channel closed before a response was received"`

…and `zip=FAIL` even though the harvest itself ran (941 posts in
`chrome.storage`). The enrichment work doesn't checkpoint to storage,
so re-dispatch restarts enrichment from scratch and hits the same wall.

**Workaround:** loop iter mode year-by-year. Each year stays under the
5-min window — the busiest observed year (2019: 428 posts; 2020: 442;
2022: 345 in full mode) finished iter-mode harvest + enrichment + zip
in 5–8 min each. Each iter run writes its own ZIP.

```bash
for Y in 2018 2019 2020 2021 2022 2023 2024 2025 2026; do
  uv run --with websockets --no-project python3 \
    tools/fb_activity_log_extension/automation/drive_via_cdp.py \
    --mode iter --year "$Y" --with-media --max-items 0
  sleep 5  # let Chrome settle between years
done
```

Bonus: iter mode often captures MORE items per year than full mode —
full-mode's per-year scroll-stable detection can fire prematurely when
the whole-archive page is huge (observed 2018: 26 items in full mode
vs 223 in iter mode). Until that's investigated, prefer iter.

**Future fix (extension side):** split `media_zip` into checkpointed
phases — `start_enrichment` returns immediately, `poll_progress` reads
from storage, `build_zip` is short. Or persist enrichment results
incrementally so re-dispatch resumes from checkpoint instead of zero.

**Don't stack CDP probes during long runs.** When the SW is doing
heavy work (mass bot fetches), opening many concurrent CDP WebSocket
connections exhausts Chrome's DevTools server. Symptom: `curl
http://localhost:9222/json/version` times out; Chrome appears hung.
Kill stacked connections (`pkill curl`, `pkill -f probe_sw_state`)
and let CDP settle ~30s. If still wedged, kill the debug Chrome
instance (find by `ps aux | grep "Chrome-debug-9222"`) — the
chrome.storage data survives across restarts, but in-flight
`media_zip` work does not.

## Rule: Use `--refresh` after long gaps

The slim profile copy doesn't auto-sync. If FB invalidates cookies
(typical: 30+ days idle) or the user updates the extension code:

```bash
bash tools/fb_activity_log_extension/automation/start_chrome.sh --refresh
```

This kills any debug-Chrome, rebuilds the slim copy from the user's
current `Default` (picks up fresh cookies + the latest extension
source), and relaunches. Adds ~30s to the run; only needed
occasionally.

## Rule: Trust the export-directory contract

`drive_via_cdp.py` triggers the extension's `media_zip` phase, which
writes a directory at `~/Downloads/fb-activity-export-v<ver>-<ts>/`
in the exact shape `extractors/activity_log.py` and `blog/management/
commands/import_posts.py` expect. **Do not** invent a custom output
format in the driver — let the extension own that contract. If the
extension's output schema needs to change, change it there and update
the importer in the same commit.

## Rule: Profile copy is a session resource, clean up when done

The `~/Library/Application Support/Google/Chrome-debug-9222` directory
is ~800MB and grows over time. Per the `large_file_hygiene.mdc` shared
rule:

- Keep one copy (refreshed in-place via `--refresh`).
- When the user is done with the automation flow for a while
  (>1 week), offer to remove it: `rm -rf ~/Library/Application\ Support/Google/Chrome-debug-9222`.
- macOS disk gets tight — see `mac_resource_hygiene.mdc` for cleanup
  candidates.

## Known gotchas

- **Service worker dormancy:** if the driver fails fast with "FB
  extension service worker not found", the SW went to sleep between
  runs. The driver should auto-wake; if it doesn't, run
  `start_chrome.sh --refresh` to force a fresh launch.
- **Tab navigation timeouts:** `waitForTabComplete` is capped at 30s per
  year. On slow networks this can fire. Check the per-year `yearMs`
  in the JSON output — anything near 30000 means we timed out the
  navigation and skipped that year.
- **FB session lapse:** if the activity log URL redirects to
  `/login`, the slim profile's cookies expired. Run
  `start_chrome.sh --refresh` so the user's freshly-logged-in
  cookies sync over.
- **Privacy-walled posts (`<title>Shared with X's friends</title>`):**
  the tab-enrichment step returns zero trusted markers and zero
  og:image. v2.8.17+ correctly ships those posts with empty media
  manifest entries; expect a chunk of `mergedCount` to have no
  associated media files.
